EXAMINATION:
MR Shoulder wo Contrast LEFT

CLINICAL INDICATION: Female, 56 years old. Pain in left shoulder M25.512 Muscle wasting and atrophy, NEC, left upper arm M62.522. Anterior left shoulder pain with referred pain into the biceps for several months. No recent injury.

TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequential MR imaging of the shoulder was performed.

CONTRAST: None

COMPARISON: None

FINDINGS:
There is abnormal, hyperintensity within the distal 1.6 cm of the posterior half of the supraspinatus tendon involving at least 75% of the width of the tendon and consistent with at least a partial tear of the bursal surface. The infraspinatus and subscapularis tendons are intact. There is no evidence of muscular atrophy.

The long head of the biceps tendon is in normal position and morphology within the bicipital groove. Glenoid labrum is unremarkable and there is no joint effusion. There is minimal cystic change within the head of the humerus measuring approximately 3 to 4 mm doubtful clinical significance. There is mild degenerative change of the AC joint with fibrous hypertrophy and there is a type II acromion process. The suprascapular notch is unremarkable. There is no Hill-Sachs deformity or Bankart lesion.

IMPRESSION:
1. Abnormal signal intensity within the distal posterior aspect of the supraspinatus tendon as described above along the bursal surface consistent with at least a high-grade partial tear. The possibility of a full-thickness tear cannot be excluded though it is not definitively present on the images.
2. Mild degenerative changes of the AC joint

Thank you for allowing us to participate in the care of this patient.
