- Orthopedist referenced indirectly (“e ortho be he was flippant”) — name/details not in records.

No insurers, radiology providers, or expert witnesses named in these pages.

## Injuries & Medical Findings
- Primary complaints (initial): right low back and right hip pain, progressing to a weak/heavy right leg and dull right ankle pain after a 9/3/2014 yoga lab.
- Ongoing complaints (2021–2022): cervical and thoracic complaints (neck/CTL), right shoulder soreness, suboccipital muscle involvement, upper trapezius and related muscle tightness/spasm, sinus/ear/facial pain noted once.
- Objective findings in chiropractic notes are limited and nonnumeric: entries list fixation/subluxation checkboxes, trigger point/muscle spasm notations (e.g., UT, RL, LS), and “HT Subocc” (suboccipital hypertonicity). No ROM measurements, standardized pain scores, or ICD diagnosis codes filled in the notes.
- Imaging: patient-reported MRI referenced in notes; no radiology report or images included in this document.
- Allergies: allergic to codeine and “other pain meds” (relevant for medication management).

## Liability & Damages Details
- Alleged causation: onset linked by patient to a yoga lab on 9/3/2014 (documented in the 9/22/15 history). This is the primary claim event listed in these records.
- Potential intervening/new injury: fall while running reported in April 2022 — could be argued by defense as an intervening cause for any worsening after that date. Needs clarification (date, circumstances, injuries from that fall).
- Preexisting condition: remote, significant trauma in 1980 (pedestrian vs auto) noted; may be used by defense to argue preexisting spine pathology. No contemporaneous records from that era supplied here.
- Treatment continuity and gaps: large gap in documented care — initial history dated 9/22/15 (describing a 2014 onset), then active chiropractic notes only appear in late 2021–2022. This multi-year gap (2015–2021) is a potential vulnerability for causation/ongoing injury arguments.
- Medical causation: records show ongoing subjective complaints and conservative chiropractic treatment but lack explicit provider opinions tying current symptoms causally to the 9/3/2014 yoga incident, or relating objective imaging to that event. No operative or definitive orthopedic interventions documented; orthopedist seen/mentioned but records not included.
- Treatment limitations: patient’s allergy to codeine/other pain meds may limit pharmacologic treatment and could support higher damages for pain if limitations are documented by treating clinicians.
- Lien/assignment language: signed intake contains a direct-assignment clause (Part B) directing third parties/attorneys to pay the clinic from settlement proceeds — useful for resolving chiropractic lien.

## Bottom Line
Strengths:
- Patient-provided contemporaneous history (9/22/15) links onset to a specific event (yoga lab 9/3/14).
- Ongoing conservative care into 2021–2022 documented with repeated visits and active treatment modalities — supports ongoing symptomology.
- Signed records/custodian affidavit authenticate the records; intake contains assignment language helpful for lien resolution.
- MRI is referenced (investigate/report) — if imaging supports structural injury, it can strengthen causation and damages.

Weaknesses / Items to address:
- Major documentation gap between 2015 history and 2021 treatment notes — defense likely to exploit lapse to challenge continuous causation/recency of complaints.
- Notes lack objective data (no ICDs, ROM, standardized pain scores) and no included imaging/radiology reports; little explicit clinician causation opinion tying current condition to the 2014 incident.
- Remote 1980 severe trauma noted — will be raised as preexisting condition; need prior records to rebut or explain residuals vs new injury.
- A reported fall in 2022 may be an intervening event; clarify timing and injuries to avoid causation issues.

Recommended next steps for plaintiff’s counsel:
1. Obtain any missing records referenced: MRI images and radiology report(s); orthopedist notes; billing records; any prior treatment records between 2014–2021 and from 1980 onward to establish baseline.
2. Request a narrative/causation statement from the treating chiropractors (and any orthopedist) linking current symptoms to the alleged 2014 incident and explaining the treatment gap.
3. Clarify details of the 4/14/22 fall (date, mechanism, injuries) and whether it aggravated or created new conditions.
4. Collect objective testing or imaging that supports structural injury (if MRI exists) and document functional limitations (work impact, activity restriction).
5. Prepare to rebut preexisting-condition arguments with medical chronology and expert review.

Flag for plaintiff: authenticated records and assignment clause are favorable; pursue MRI and treating-provider causation opinion and fill the treatment-history gaps to shore up linkage to the 2014 event.', 'Medical Records', 1, 'Admin', 16136739, '2026-03-12T21:03:57.434Z', 'firm', 6, 0, NULL, NULL, '{}', NULL, 'complete', NULL),
