PLAINTIFF’S SECOND SET OF INTERROGATORIES  TO DEFENDANT



	COMES NOW the Plaintiff, Erika Corey Turner, by and through her undersigned counsel, and pursuant to the Alabama Rules of Civil Procedure, propounds the following Interrogatories upon Defendant Chong Suk Thwaites, to be answered fully and completely within the time frame required by law:

DEFINITIONS

Unless otherwise indicated, the following definitions shall be applicable to these Discovery Requests:

1.	"YOU" and "YOUR" shall mean: the Defendant(s) to whom these discovery requests are directed, including their attorneys, experts (including without limitation, their expert’s contractors, subcontractors, agents and employees), employees, agents, representatives and all other persons acting on their behalf.

2.	The term "COMMUNICATION" or "COMMUNICATIONS" or "COMMUNICATE" shall mean and include: any transaction or exchange of information or words between two or more persons, whether orally or in writing, and includes without limitation, by means of letter, telephone, note, memorandum, telegraph, telefax, telecopier, cable, computer, any electronic or other medium, audio, video, computer disk or computer tape.

3.	The term "DOCUMENT" or "DOCUMENTS" shall mean and include: writings of any kind, formal or informal, whether or not wholly or partially in handwriting, including without limitation, any invoice, receipt, endorsement, check, bank draft, canceled check, deposit slip, withdrawal slip, order, correspondence, record, record book, minutes, memorandum of telephone or other conversation (including meetings, agreements and the like), diary, calendar, desk pad, scrapbook, notebook, bulletin, circular, form pamphlet, statement, journal, postcard, letter, telegram, telex, telefax, report, notice, message, analysis, comparison, graph, chart, interoffice or intraoffice communications, photostat or other copy of any documents, microfilm or other film record, photograph, sound recording on any type of device, computer data, punch card, disc or disc pact, tape, recording, any type of memory generally associated with computers and data processing (together with the programming instructions and other written material necessary to use such punch card, disc, or disc pact, tape or other type of memory and together with printouts of such punch card, disc, or disc pact, tape or other type of memory, including: (a) every copy of each document which is not any exact duplicate of a document which is produced, (b) every copy which has any writing, figure or notation, annotation or the lack of it, (c) drafts, (d) attachments to or enclosures with any document, (e) every document referred to in any other document, (f) all original file folders in which each such document is contained).

4.	The terms "PERSON" or "PERSONNEL" means and includes: natural person, firm, association, organization, partnership, business trust, corporation, or public entity.

5.	The term "CORRESPONDENCE" means and includes, without limitation: any letter, note, memorandum, facsimile, electronic mail, telegram, telex, notice, report, statement, and all other types or forms of exchanged information, whether made by hand, computer, typewriter, printer, pen, pencil, or other medium or form of recording.

6.	The use of singular forms of words used in these discovery requests shall include and mean the plural form, and vice versa. The use of gendered words in these discovery requests shall mean and include both genders.

7.	Wherever it is necessary to bring, within the scope of these requests, DOCUMENTS that might otherwise be construed to be outside their scope: (1) use of "and" as well as "or" shall be construed both disjunctively and conjunctively; (2) use of "include" and "including" shall be construed to mean "without limitation"; and (3) use of a verb in any tense or voice shall be construed as the use of that verb in all other tenses and voices.

8.	If any of the DOCUMENTS requested herein is withheld under a claim of privilege: identify each such DOCUMENT and state the date of the original DOCUMENT’S creation; identify its author and addressee, including each PERSON to whom copies of the DOCUMENT were furnished and to whom the contents thereon were COMMUNICATED; include a summary of the subject matter of the DOCUMENT; include the DOCUMENT’S present location and custodian; include the basis upon which the asserted privilege is claimed; and include the request to which the DOCUMENT is responsive.

9.	If any of the DOCUMENTS requested herein has been destroyed, furnish a list identifying: each such DOCUMENT; its author and addressee; each PERSON to whom copies of the DOCUMENT were furnished and to whom the contents thereof were communicated; a summary of the substance of the DOCUMENT; the date upon which it was destroyed; and the reason it was destroyed.

10.	As used herein, the term "COMPLAINT" shall refer to and include the complaint filed in the above-captioned matter.

11.	The term "PROBLEM" or "PROBLEMS" mean and include: any criticism, question, claim, notice, complaint, issue, grievance, conclusion, belief, opinion, concern, charge or protest, whether written or oral, whether noted, observed or communicated by a person not employed by Defendant or noted, observed or communicated by a person employed by the Defendant.

12.	The terms "IDENTIFY" or "IDENTIFICATION," when used in reference to a PERSON, shall mean: to state the full name, the present or last known address, and the telephone number of such PERSON, as well as his/her place of employment and job title.

13.	The terms "IDENTIFY" or "IDENTIFICATION," when used in reference to a document, shall mean: to state its date; its author or signer and their address; type of document; all other means of identifying it; its present or last known location; and its custodian. If any document was, but is no longer in, your possession, custody or control, state what disposition was made of it and the reason for its disposition.

14.	The term "REPORT" or "REPORTS" shall include, without limitation: any CORRESPONDENCE or COMMUNICATION wherein there is contained any criticism, question, complaint, claim, notice, issue, grievance, conclusion, belief, opinion, concern, charge or protest, whether written or oral, and whether noted, observed or communicated by a person not employed by Defendant or noted, observed or communicated by a person employed by the Defendant.

15.	The term “PLAINTIFF’S VEHICLE” shall mean: the vehicle Plaintiff was occupying at the time of the accident or collision which is the basis of this lawsuit.

16. 	The term “THIS ACCIDENT,” “THE ACCDENT” and “COLLISION” shall mean: the accident or collision which is the basis of this lawsuit.

  	In answering these Interrogatories, please furnish all information known to you and available to you, including information in the possession of your attorneys, investigators, agents, or by anyone acting on your behalf or under your control. 

	If any of these Interrogatories cannot be answered in full, please answer to the extent possible, specifying the reason for your inability to answer the remainder and stating whatever knowledge or information that you have concerning the unanswered portion.

You are under a duty to seasonably amend a prior response if you obtain information upon the basis of which you know that the response, through correct when made, is no longer true, and the circumstances are such that a failure to amend the response is, in substance, a knowing concealment.



INTERROGATORIES

1.	State the name and address of all doctors and physicians, hospital, medical institutions, and nurses of any kind, who have treated you during the (10) year period prior to the occasion of the occurrence or accident made the basis of your suit and state specifically the illnesses, diseases or physical problems for which you were so treated by such doctors.

