ANSWER OF DEFENDANT CHONG SUK THWAITES



	Comes now CHONG SUK THWAITES, a Defendant in the above styled cause and in response to the Complaint heretofore filed by the Plaintiff, sayeth as follows:

COUNTS ONE AND TWO

NEGLIGENCE OR WANTONNESS



	1.	Your Defendant admits that he was operating a motor vehicle on the date and at the location set forth in Counts One and Two of the Plaintiff’s Complaint.

	2.	Your Defendant denies the remaining allegations contained in Counts One and Two of the Plaintiff’s Complaint and hereby demands strict proof thereof.

COUNTS THREE AND FOUR

NEGLIGENCE OR WANTONNESS

(FICTITIOUS DEFENDANTS A-D)



	The allegations contained in Counts Three and Four of Plaintiff’s Complaint do not pertain to this Defendant.  Your Defendant therefore neither admits nor denies the allegations contained therein.	

FIRST AFFIRMATIVE DEFENSE

	The Defendant avers the Plaintiff herself was guilty of negligence which proximately cause or contributed to the damages of which she complains and therefore ought not recover.

SECOND AFFIRMATIVE DEFENSE

	The Defendant avers the Plaintiff has failed to mitigate her damages.

THIRD AFFIRMATIVE DEFENSE



		To the extent that the Plaintiff’s Complaint demands punitive damages, the following affirmative defenses are asserted:

	1.	Punitive damages, as awarded pursuant to the procedures set forth by the Alabama Supreme Court in Life Insurance Company of Georgia v. Johnson, Alabama Supreme Court Number 1940357, November 17, 1995, are unconstitutional and violate the Fourth, Fifth, Sixth, Eighth and Fourteenth Amendments of the Constitution of the United States and Articles I, III, IV, VI, XI and Sections 1, 6, 10, 15 and 22 of Article I of the Constitution of the State of Alabama on the following separate and several grounds:

	(a)	The procedures may result in the award of joint and several judgments against joint tortfeasors.

	(b)	The procedures fail to provide means forwarding separate judgments against tortfeasors.

	(c)	The procedures fail to provide a limit on the amount of the award against this Defendant in violation of this Defendant''s rights to procedural and substantive due process.

	(d)	The procedures fail to provide specific standards for the award of punitive damages.

	(e)	The procedures fail to provide specific standards for the amount of the award of punitive damages.

	(f)	The procedures permit the award of punitive damages upon satisfaction of reduced standard of proof.

	(g)	The procedures permit multiple awards of punitive damages for the same alleged act.

	(h) 	The procedures fail to provide a clear and consistent appellate standard of review for an award of punitive damages.

	(i)	The procedures permit the admission of evidence relative to punitive damages in the same proceeding during which liability and compensatory damages are determined.

	(j)	The procedures do not provide adequate guidelines for the jury to follow in making a decision as to the amount to be awarded, if any, as punitive damages.

	(k)	The award of punitive damages violates the Excessive Fines Clause of the Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution and the Excessive Fines Clause of the Alabama Constitution.

	(l)	An award of punitive damages as claimed would violate this Defendant''s right to equal protection under the law.

	(m)	An award of punitive damages as claimed would violate this Defendant''s right to substantive and procedural due process.

	(n)	The procedures pursuant to which Plaintiff’s demand for punitive damages are unconstitutionally vague.

	(o)	The guidelines by which juries determine the amount, if any, of punitive damages are unconstitutionally vague.

	(p)	An award of punitive damages in this action would constitute a deprivation of property without due process of law under the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments of the United States Constitution.

	(q)	The award of punitive damages against a civil defendant without providing to that defendant all of the protections guaranteed to a person accused of a crime violates the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment and the requirements of the Fifth and Sixth Amendments.

	(r)	In creating the procedure for the determination and award of punitive damages, the Supreme Court of the State of Alabama violated the Separation of Powers provision of the Constitution of the State of Alabama.

	(s)	In creating the procedure for the determination and award of punitive damages, the Supreme Court of the United States exceeded the scope of its enumerated powers as provided in the Constitution of the State of Alabama.

	(t)	In failing to provide proper guidelines regarding the admissibility of evidence in the bifurcated proceedings for the determination and award of punitive damages, the Supreme Court of the State of Alabama exceeded its statutory and constitutional authority.

	(u)	The failure to provide proper guidelines regarding the admissibility of evidence in the bifurcated proceedings for the award and distribution of punitive damages results renders said procedure being constitutionally vague and violative of the Constitution of the United States of America and the State of Alabama.

THE DEFENDANT RESPECTFULLY DEMANDS A TRIAL BY JURY



  /s/ Matthew A. Laymon                             

MATTHEW A. LAYMON, ESQ. (LAY006)

