Page 1 of 1 11-21-25', '## Key Facts & Timeline
- Patient: Erika Corey Turner, DOB 6/05/1965. Records produced by Mobile Oral Surgery (custodian: Suzanne Walley). Allergies: Penicillin and Codeine.
- 10/26/2023: Referral placed (referring provider signature 10/26/23 — requests extraction of tooth #19).
- 10/30/2023: Initial oral surgery evaluation — tooth #19 nonrestorable; treatment plan = extraction of #19 and bone graft under general anesthesia. Risks discussed (including inferior alveolar/lingual nerve damage, TMJ dysfunction, infection, bleeding, oroantral communication). Past history includes prior jaw surgery and TMJ symptoms.
- 11/07/2023: Surgical record — extraction of tooth #19 and bone graft performed under general anesthesia. No intraoperative complications documented; estimated blood loss <10 cc.
- 11/09/2023: Post-op visit — complaints of dizziness and “b jaw pressure”; instructed to syringe irrigate, stop meds, warm compresses, soft diet.
- 11/14/2023, 01/09/2024: Routine follow-ups — well healed.
- 06/11/2024: Implant placement (endosteal implant #19) under general/deep sedation; operative note documents implant placement and no complications.
- 06/12–06/18/2024: Post-op call (message left) and post-op visit (6/18/24) — satisfactory healing; irrigation instructions; implant stable on exam.
- 09/18/2024: Follow-up — implant stable; panoramic radiograph shows good osseointegration. Cleared for restorative work with Grelot Dental.
- 11/18/2024: Follow-up notation — patient had pain and swelling previously; office called in clindamycin; infection has completely resolved. No active infection on exam; released to complete restorative phase.

## People Mentioned (with roles)
- Erika Turner — patient / plaintiff.
- Christopher Mullenix, DMD, MD — treating oral & maxillofacial surgeon (primary provider in notes).
- Aaron Wallender, DDS, MD — practice partner (listed on letterhead).
- Tommy Hannher — referring dentist (signed 10/26/23).
- Surgical assistants: A K (assistant), anesthesia assistant Gazzier (11/11/24?), Heather Lander (11/07/23 anesthesia assistant).
- Anesthesia personnel referenced (deep sedation/general anesthesia billed).
- Custodian of Records: Suzanne Walley (Mobile Oral Surgery).
- Notary: Molly Gager.
- Grelot Dental — restorative dentist identified to complete final restoration.
- No insurers or independent experts identified in these records.

## Injuries & Medical Findings
- Dental pathology: Tooth #19 carious/fractured, nonrestorable — required extraction, ridge preservation bone graft, and subsequent implant placement.
- Procedures:
  - 11/07/2023: Surgical extraction of #19 + bone graft (ridge preservation).
  - 06/11/2024: Endosteal implant placement at #19 (D6010).
- Post-operative events:
  - 11/09/2023: Dizziness and bilateral jaw pressure reported after extraction.
  - 11/18/2024: Pain and swelling consistent with postoperative infection — treated with clindamycin (appropriate due to penicillin allergy) and documented as resolved on exam.
- Imaging: Panoramic radiographs (10/30/23, 01/09/24, 06/18/24, 09/18/24) showing implant in place and “good take” / osseointegration by 9/18/24.
- No documentation of permanent nerve injury, persistent numbness/paresthesia, oroantral communication, or other lasting complication in these notes.

## Liability & Damages Details
- Fault indicators: These are treatment records — no third-party liability or causal event external to the dental condition is described. No documentation suggesting provider negligence; intraoperative notes repeatedly state “no complications.”
- Medical causation: Records show a temporal link between procedure(s) and transient post-op complications (dizziness/jaw pressure; a later infection with pain/swelling). Infection was treated and resolved. The extraction and implant were clearly medically justified based on tooth #19 being nonrestorable.
- Comparative negligence: Not applicable in these records (no external incident or patient-contributed fault noted).
- Treatment gaps / continuity:
  - Follow-up appears consistent: timely post-op visits and calls after both extraction and implant placement.
  - Infection episode: treated promptly with clindamycin and documented resolved; no gap in care documented.
- Economic damages evidence:
  - Ledger shows billed/paid items tied to the extractions, bone graft, anesthesia, and implant placement (e.g., D6010 implant placement $2,000; anesthesia charges; D7210 extraction $300; D7953 bone graft $600). Payments recorded (CareCredit and patient payments) — useful to document out-of-pocket / billed costs.
- Medical risks disclosed: Consent notes show patient was informed pre-op of possible nerve damage, TMJ dysfunction, infection, bleeding, etc. No subsequent documentation of those major adverse outcomes except transient symptoms and a resolved infection.

## Bottom Line
These records document definitive surgical treatment for a nonrestorable lower molar (#19): extraction with bone graft (11/07/23) and later implant placement (06/11/24). Post-op complications were limited and transient: a post-extraction report of dizziness/jaw pressure (11/09/23) and a later episode of pain and swelling treated as a postoperative infection with clindamycin (noted resolved 11/18/24). Imaging and exam entries show good implant integration and the patient was repeatedly cleared for restorative completion. No permanent nerve injury or ongoing infection is documented. Relevant evidence to support a personal injury claim for dental damages: precise procedure dates, operative reports (no intra-op complications), documentation of post-op infection requiring antibiotic treatment, and itemized charges/payments for procedures and anesthesia. Allergies (penicillin, codeine) are documented and explain antibiotic selection.', 'Medical Records', 1, 'Admin', 760718, '2026-03-12T21:04:19.994Z', 'firm', 6, 0, NULL, NULL, '{}', NULL, 'complete', NULL),
